1
00:02:22,308 --> 00:02:23,811
Great day to watch a game.

2
00:02:23,921 --> 00:02:27,175
But first things first.
More important things to do.

3
00:02:31,983 --> 00:02:33,161
Thomas to Stevens.

4
00:02:37,283 --> 00:02:38,562
ETA 1700.

5
00:02:39,389 --> 00:02:40,399
Thank you.

6
00:02:47,221 --> 00:02:50,408
The Cherokees and the Mammoths
with the right to go on to the playoffs.

7
00:02:50,513 --> 00:02:53,834
And their biggest fan, President Harmon,
who hasn't missed a game all season...

8
00:02:53,935 --> 00:02:55,708
is not here today. Can you believe it?

9
00:02:55,812 --> 00:02:57,550
It's true, Dave. But for a good reason.

10
00:02:57,654 --> 00:02:59,595
Instead he's attending
the National Merit Awards...

11
00:02:59,695 --> 00:03:01,142
at Arlington University.

12
00:03:01,241 --> 00:03:04,562
And I got a feeling that somehow
he's gonna get to a radio or television.

13
00:03:04,665 --> 00:03:07,750
- There's no way he's gonna miss this one.
- You're absolutely right, Ernie.

14
00:03:07,857 --> 00:03:10,347
And I believe that we are set now
for the kickoff...

15
00:03:10,457 --> 00:03:12,824
and you are about to see it live.

16
00:03:26,090 --> 00:03:27,436
So, Alex...

17
00:03:29,381 --> 00:03:33,263
- who won the last game?
- I did, Mr. President.

18
00:03:33,693 --> 00:03:36,554
That makes three in a row?

19
00:03:38,267 --> 00:03:41,588
- Yeah. Honey?
- Oh, yes.

20
00:03:43,928 --> 00:03:46,688
It's too bad
that this speech had to be today...

21
00:03:46,791 --> 00:03:50,180
since it's the last home game
you could officially see as President.

22
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:52,086
But they're gonna be
a lot more fun to watch...

23
00:03:52,189 --> 00:03:54,623
when I don't have to run a country
at the same time.

24
00:03:54,723 --> 00:03:58,605
Oh, boy, state dinners every night
do get a bit old.

25
00:03:59,034 --> 00:04:03,208
I can hardly wait to curl up on the couch
with a box of Krispy Kremes.

26
00:04:05,880 --> 00:04:06,991
Alex.

27
00:04:09,138 --> 00:04:11,933
- Thank you, Mr. President.
- You're welcome.

28
00:04:37,936 --> 00:04:40,034
Okay. The other side, ma'am.

29
00:04:42,543 --> 00:04:44,215
- Thank you.
- Thanks.

30
00:04:54,819 --> 00:04:56,659
And here's Mr. Stevens.

31
00:04:57,584 --> 00:05:00,344
Stevens! Mr. Stevens!

32
00:05:01,204 --> 00:05:02,617
Okay, thanks.

33
00:05:02,718 --> 00:05:04,031
Excuse me.

34
00:05:06,634 --> 00:05:11,100
The President has decided to spend
a few minutes with you upon his arrival.

35
00:05:11,834 --> 00:05:13,640
And he should be here shortly.

36
00:05:13,743 --> 00:05:17,098
Mr. Stevens, is the President
backing the Vice President?

37
00:05:17,199 --> 00:05:20,060
Mr. Stevens, can you tell us about security?

38
00:05:23,123 --> 00:05:24,728
We're on approach.

39
00:05:28,652 --> 00:05:29,932
Excuse me.

40
00:06:48,297 --> 00:06:50,362
Gun!

41
00:07:07,123 --> 00:07:08,929
Get Air Med over here!

42
00:07:26,178 --> 00:07:28,838
Get Air Med over here, now!

43
00:07:46,814 --> 00:07:50,629
We're en route to your location
with the President of the United States.

44
00:07:51,323 --> 00:07:54,184
He has a gunshot wound to the head,
one entry wound.

45
00:07:54,285 --> 00:07:55,923
Patient is trauma-coded.

46
00:07:56,029 --> 00:07:58,857
We have a large-bore lV running wide open.

47
00:07:59,156 --> 00:08:00,761
ETA is in five minutes.

48
00:08:11,366 --> 00:08:14,979
I'm just gonna go to the closest hospital.
I guess that's where they're gonna take him.

49
00:08:15,250 --> 00:08:16,529
All right.

50
00:08:17,751 --> 00:08:19,198
And let me know if you need anything.

51
00:08:19,298 --> 00:08:22,159
Okay, thanks.
I'll call you as soon as I have something.

52
00:08:29,006 --> 00:08:30,779
There they are. Let's go.

53
00:08:35,852 --> 00:08:37,557
Hurry up. This way.

54
00:08:38,814 --> 00:08:40,519
- Secured.
- Locking.

55
00:08:51,353 --> 00:08:53,586
Whoa, whoa, whoa!
You have an open wound. You're not sterile.

56
00:08:53,690 --> 00:08:55,564
I can't leave his side. He's my responsibility.

57
00:08:55,665 --> 00:08:57,303
In here, he's my responsibility.

58
00:08:57,409 --> 00:08:59,115
Nurse, take him to the ER.

59
00:08:59,219 --> 00:09:01,744
I'll be with him all the way through.

60
00:09:47,895 --> 00:09:51,441
You're a lucky man. X-ray looks good.
No broken bones.

61
00:09:51,910 --> 00:09:55,164
Take it easy on the hand for a few weeks.
You'll be fine.

62
00:10:22,683 --> 00:10:24,355
Feels like forever.

63
00:10:27,389 --> 00:10:30,609
- How's the hand?
- Fine, thank you, ma'am.

64
00:10:34,695 --> 00:10:35,772
Alex.

65
00:10:39,566 --> 00:10:41,036
You were there.

66
00:10:48,716 --> 00:10:50,062
How was he?

67
00:10:53,916 --> 00:10:55,823
Alex, please talk to me.

68
00:10:59,675 --> 00:11:01,414
It didn't look good.

69
00:11:15,900 --> 00:11:18,065
I need a minute to myself.

70
00:11:21,067 --> 00:11:22,245
Doctor...

71
00:11:23,635 --> 00:11:26,922
- would you please inform the press?
- Of course.

72
00:11:27,024 --> 00:11:28,303
Thank you.

73
00:11:31,763 --> 00:11:33,996
Ma'am, I'm sorry for your loss.

74
00:11:35,318 --> 00:11:38,269
If you need a few private moments
with him...

75
00:11:39,070 --> 00:11:41,437
I don't want to see him like that.

76
00:11:56,678 --> 00:11:58,416
Special Agent Thomas?

77
00:11:59,968 --> 00:12:02,863
Hi, I'm Kate Crawford
from the Washington Inlander.

78
00:12:02,964 --> 00:12:04,635
I know who you are.

79
00:12:05,069 --> 00:12:07,829
Then talk to me. You might need a friend.

80
00:12:08,492 --> 00:12:09,703
Let's go.

81
00:12:38,474 --> 00:12:40,011
- Hey.
- Hi.

82
00:12:43,971 --> 00:12:46,530
How did you get into his army records?

83
00:12:48,315 --> 00:12:50,548
Never mind. I don't want to know.

84
00:12:51,870 --> 00:12:54,630
Your sources,
have they given you anything?

85
00:12:54,996 --> 00:12:58,642
Well, the Secret Service had him on file
as a Class Three threat case.

86
00:12:58,748 --> 00:12:59,723
Crank letter writer.

87
00:12:59,834 --> 00:13:01,831
Then how the hell did he get
anywhere near the President?

88
00:13:01,941 --> 00:13:04,925
Because they don't assign agents
to high-level threat cases...

89
00:13:05,034 --> 00:13:08,513
unless they live in the immediate area.
Detimore's not from here.

90
00:13:09,544 --> 00:13:12,730
So you don't know anything
that anybody else doesn't know.

91
00:13:12,834 --> 00:13:15,201
Bite me, Peter. The guy's a ghost.

92
00:13:15,566 --> 00:13:18,225
He has no bank statements,
he has no credit records.

93
00:13:18,330 --> 00:13:20,102
He paid his rent in cash.

94
00:13:20,206 --> 00:13:23,067
And, oddly enough,
his personal history's been erased...

95
00:13:23,168 --> 00:13:25,333
since he left the army in '92.

96
00:13:26,888 --> 00:13:28,986
I'm gonna go back to the campus.

97
00:13:29,092 --> 00:13:32,380
See if I can talk to anyone
who saw him yesterday.

98
00:13:32,482 --> 00:13:34,513
Get a different take on it.

99
00:13:35,774 --> 00:13:40,117
Fine, but I want daily reports.
Not your usual out-of-contact-for-weeks.

100
00:13:44,396 --> 00:13:46,887
You know, an e-mail would also
work for me.

101
00:13:59,568 --> 00:14:01,599
It's not gonna last forever, you know?

102
00:14:01,708 --> 00:14:05,490
Don't worry about it, Bri.
I understand procedure.

103
00:14:07,401 --> 00:14:08,748
To be honest with you...

104
00:14:08,849 --> 00:14:11,283
I could use the time
to get my head on straight...

105
00:14:11,384 --> 00:14:13,123
think things through.

106
00:14:13,293 --> 00:14:16,221
Hey, hey, cut yourself some slack, man.

107
00:14:17,932 --> 00:14:22,432
We've gone over every second of that day.
You did everything by the book.

108
00:14:25,503 --> 00:14:27,960
Stevens was looking for you earlier.

109
00:14:29,715 --> 00:14:33,228
Listen. If you need anything, call me.

110
00:14:33,961 --> 00:14:35,004
Okay?

111
00:14:43,012 --> 00:14:44,189
Come in.

112
00:14:45,216 --> 00:14:46,854
I heard you were looking for me, sir?

113
00:14:46,961 --> 00:14:50,315
Agent Thomas,
I know you're required to take time off.

114
00:14:50,450 --> 00:14:52,581
But keep in touch,
because when all this clears...

115
00:14:52,688 --> 00:14:54,595
- I'm gonna need you back.
- Yes, sir.

116
00:14:54,695 --> 00:14:57,523
And do not blame yourself
for what happened.

117
00:14:59,171 --> 00:15:02,358
It wouldn't have changed direction
if it didn't go through my hand first, sir.

118
00:15:02,462 --> 00:15:03,842
Now, listen.

119
00:15:05,325 --> 00:15:08,714
You took a bullet for the man.
Nobody can ask for more than that.

120
00:15:08,814 --> 00:15:10,025
Yes, sir.

121
00:15:35,801 --> 00:15:38,663
Please stop at that area, but just stay back.

122
00:15:38,763 --> 00:15:40,076
Thank you.

123
00:15:41,956 --> 00:15:44,413
- That's far enough.
- All right. Okay.

124
00:15:47,057 --> 00:15:49,749
Don't mind him.
He's always out here begging.

125
00:15:49,855 --> 00:15:51,594
He won't bother you.

126
00:15:52,389 --> 00:15:53,836
Okay. Thanks.

127
00:15:59,399 --> 00:16:00,678
Excuse me?

128
00:16:02,164 --> 00:16:03,207
Hi.

129
00:16:03,612 --> 00:16:07,652
- May I talk with you for a minute?
- Arthur Fuller's the name.

130
00:16:08,351 --> 00:16:10,808
My friends call me Shakey.

131
00:16:11,971 --> 00:16:13,441
My name's Kate.

132
00:16:14,736 --> 00:16:17,193
- Cool kicks, Shakey.
- Zip-a-dee-doo.

133
00:16:17,730 --> 00:16:19,110
It's a look.

134
00:16:21,548 --> 00:16:23,983
Were you here
when the President was assassinated?

135
00:16:24,082 --> 00:16:25,159
Yeah.

136
00:16:26,518 --> 00:16:27,797
Bad scene.

137
00:16:28,163 --> 00:16:30,755
Did you see the shooter here, that day?

138
00:16:40,308 --> 00:16:41,283
No.

139
00:16:43,270 --> 00:16:44,807
Not around here.

140
00:16:46,166 --> 00:16:47,636
Wait, wait. Sorry?

141
00:16:48,371 --> 00:16:51,031
When you say
that you didn't see him around here...

142
00:16:51,135 --> 00:16:53,043
do you mean
that you haven't seen him at all...

143
00:16:53,143 --> 00:16:54,882
or that you've seen him somewhere else?

144
00:16:54,986 --> 00:16:56,366
I've seen him where he lived.

145
00:16:56,467 --> 00:16:58,409
Where? Where have you seen him?

146
00:16:58,869 --> 00:17:02,549
Well, for $20, I'll show you.

147
00:17:17,202 --> 00:17:18,514
Shangri-la.

148
00:17:18,879 --> 00:17:22,559
- You sure he was living here?
- Scout's honor.

149
00:17:24,212 --> 00:17:25,715
Cross my heart.

150
00:17:27,305 --> 00:17:29,998
- That's my home away from home.
- It's nice.

151
00:17:30,102 --> 00:17:32,167
Yeah, wait until you see the inside.

152
00:17:38,988 --> 00:17:40,727
Hey, boss. You got company.

153
00:17:40,832 --> 00:17:42,829
- How many?
- Two. Man and a woman.

154
00:17:48,994 --> 00:17:52,012
Your boy was living there about a week.

155
00:17:53,536 --> 00:17:55,736
Did you tell anyone else about this?

156
00:17:55,839 --> 00:18:00,439
No. Nobody ever asks me nothing.
I don't volunteer nothing.

157
00:18:02,817 --> 00:18:03,860
Yeah.

158
00:18:04,791 --> 00:18:06,104
Okay, look.

159
00:18:08,905 --> 00:18:11,991
Can you stand out here and keep watch?
Let me know if anyone comes, okay?

160
00:18:12,097 --> 00:18:14,038
- I can do that.
- All right.

161
00:18:14,138 --> 00:18:16,999
Buy yourself a couple of beers
or something. Okay?

162
00:18:17,100 --> 00:18:18,547
I don't drink.

163
00:18:20,786 --> 00:18:21,830
Okay.

164
00:18:28,652 --> 00:18:30,458
I'll give you another $20
when I come out, okay?

165
00:18:30,561 --> 00:18:31,638
Yeah.

166
00:19:54,781 --> 00:19:57,306
- Hey.
- Hey, boss.

167
00:19:59,060 --> 00:20:01,001
Listen, a last question.

168
00:20:01,298 --> 00:20:03,665
Did you ever see him with anyone?

169
00:20:04,589 --> 00:20:08,797
Oh, yeah. Yeah, twice. Twice!
I seen a guy go into the place.

170
00:20:08,900 --> 00:20:10,572
Okay, great, that's great.

171
00:20:10,677 --> 00:20:13,111
- Would you recognize him again?
- Yeah, yeah.

172
00:20:13,277 --> 00:20:15,341
- Did you run her plates?
- Yes, sir.

173
00:20:15,450 --> 00:20:17,884
Give me a few hours
and I'll have her life's history.

174
00:20:20,123 --> 00:20:23,310
Look, I gotta go, okay? But thank you.

175
00:20:23,414 --> 00:20:25,377
- Thank you for all your help. All right?
- Yeah.

176
00:20:25,487 --> 00:20:27,720
- Okay.
- Come back, I'll buy you dinner.

177
00:20:28,318 --> 00:20:30,685
Okay. How much will that cost me?

178
00:20:56,556 --> 00:20:58,923
- Yeah?
- Hey, it's Kate. Okay, listen.

179
00:20:59,024 --> 00:21:01,257
Detimore wasn't working alone
on this thing.

180
00:21:01,361 --> 00:21:04,715
A third party rented him an apartment.
They paid cash.

181
00:21:05,442 --> 00:21:09,583
Two weeks before the shooting,
it's near campus and it's under a false name.

182
00:21:09,687 --> 00:21:11,853
And I met a guy named Shakey...

183
00:21:11,958 --> 00:21:16,065
and he lives in a van behind the building,
but he swears he can lD him.

184
00:21:16,269 --> 00:21:20,769
Shakey? Let me guess.
Drunk, needs a shower, not all there.

185
00:21:21,403 --> 00:21:24,063
Yeah, but he knows what he saw
and I believe him.

186
00:21:24,168 --> 00:21:26,233
And listen, I went into the apartment...

187
00:21:26,340 --> 00:21:30,717
and I found cough syrup,
and bloody tissues, and painkillers.

188
00:21:31,244 --> 00:21:32,254
Which means?

189
00:21:32,594 --> 00:21:35,713
Which means he had lung cancer.
I saw the same thing with my mom.

190
00:21:37,860 --> 00:21:38,970
Right.

191
00:21:40,163 --> 00:21:42,194
So maybe the guy wanted to go out
in a blaze of glory.

192
00:21:42,664 --> 00:21:44,168
Or someone found out and used him.

193
00:21:44,277 --> 00:21:46,218
Go back to Shakey's,
find out what else he knows.

194
00:21:46,318 --> 00:21:47,328
Okay.

195
00:22:16,465 --> 00:22:18,529
- Hold it, ma'am.
- Kate Crawford, Washington Inlander.

196
00:22:18,637 --> 00:22:19,714
Okay.

197
00:22:25,614 --> 00:22:26,825
Hold it.

198
00:22:36,540 --> 00:22:39,469
Okay, this goes in the back. I'll radio ahead.

199
00:22:41,313 --> 00:22:43,747
So, Shakey tells me
that he can identify someone...

200
00:22:43,847 --> 00:22:45,721
that's going in and out
of Detimore's apartment...

201
00:22:45,822 --> 00:22:48,155
and, the next thing you know,
he's killed in a fire.

202
00:22:48,257 --> 00:22:49,637
That's not a coincidence.

203
00:22:49,738 --> 00:22:52,690
If he was murdered,
you're playing with big-boys rules now.

204
00:22:52,799 --> 00:22:54,269
I've played big-boy rules before.

205
00:22:54,378 --> 00:22:56,443
Yeah, and my head ended up
on the chopping block.

206
00:22:56,550 --> 00:22:58,985
Yeah, but we also won a Pulitzer.

207
00:23:01,060 --> 00:23:02,137
True.

208
00:23:03,725 --> 00:23:06,586
But this Pulitzer could end up killing you.

209
00:23:06,721 --> 00:23:10,300
- Maybe we should bring in the authorities.
- No. Come on, not yet.

210
00:23:10,407 --> 00:23:14,155
It just... They'd only shut me out
and then I'd have nothing.

211
00:23:15,804 --> 00:23:17,015
I located his sister.

212
00:23:17,121 --> 00:23:20,734
She... She lives near Warren.
I'm gonna go see her tomorrow.

213
00:23:26,303 --> 00:23:29,557
Listen, Kate. Be careful.

214
00:23:32,029 --> 00:23:35,283
Yeah, yeah. Anything for you.
I'll see you later.

215
00:24:02,768 --> 00:24:05,563
Get Air Med over here, now!

216
00:24:13,201 --> 00:24:15,434
- Hi.
- Alex, please.

217
00:24:15,670 --> 00:24:19,024
Now that he's gone,
you're the only one I can talk to.

218
00:24:19,257 --> 00:24:20,704
Not right now.

219
00:25:10,368 --> 00:25:11,546
Hold on.

220
00:26:50,880 --> 00:26:53,606
- Are you Thelma Detimore?
- And you are?

221
00:26:54,533 --> 00:26:57,977
I'm Kate Crawford
from the Washington Inlander.

222
00:26:59,898 --> 00:27:03,252
Look, I been talking to the cops all day
and I'm tired.

223
00:27:03,353 --> 00:27:06,079
You here to make him into a monster, too?

224
00:27:06,348 --> 00:27:09,894
- I'm here to get the truth.
- He was a good brother and a good son.

225
00:27:10,001 --> 00:27:12,301
- Who is it, Thelma?
- A reporter.

226
00:27:12,404 --> 00:27:14,468
Don't worry, I'll handle it.

227
00:27:15,563 --> 00:27:16,573
Is that your mother?

228
00:27:16,683 --> 00:27:19,544
She's an old lady who just outlived her son.

229
00:27:19,907 --> 00:27:21,354
Leave her be.

230
00:27:23,956 --> 00:27:25,000
Okay.

231
00:27:26,194 --> 00:27:28,528
You know what? Just one question.

232
00:27:31,229 --> 00:27:33,394
How long was he taking these?

233
00:27:35,409 --> 00:27:36,789
Long enough.

234
00:27:39,030 --> 00:27:42,440
Got it during the Gulf War.
At least that's what he always said.

235
00:27:43,735 --> 00:27:46,787
All right, look, if you think of anything...

236
00:27:47,158 --> 00:27:50,771
you know, you'd like me to know or...
Just give me a call.

237
00:27:51,831 --> 00:27:53,278
I'll do that.

238
00:27:54,431 --> 00:27:55,901
Okay, bye-bye.

239
00:28:03,416 --> 00:28:06,502
Delia, could you give me
a hand with this, please?

240
00:28:15,166 --> 00:28:17,129
Follow her and find out who she talks to.

241
00:28:57,457 --> 00:28:59,656
Thelma, the TV's broke.

242
00:29:13,551 --> 00:29:15,751
Mom! We gotta get out.

243
00:29:37,806 --> 00:29:40,140
- Sir.
- Martin.

244
00:29:42,283 --> 00:29:43,887
Very nice turnout.

245
00:29:44,159 --> 00:29:47,054
- Where's Thomas?
- At home, I'm sure.

246
00:29:47,417 --> 00:29:50,536
Taking a little time
to get himself together, sir.

247
00:29:50,741 --> 00:29:52,210
Understandable.

248
00:29:53,045 --> 00:29:54,851
It's a difficult time.

249
00:30:07,427 --> 00:30:11,770
- How's the investigation going?
